    <p>While creatine's strength and power benefits apply equally to both sexes, several research areas show particularly promising results for women.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="brain" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Cognitive Enhancement</h3>
        <p>Women have lower baseline brain creatine stores than men. A 2018 study in <em>Experimental Gerontology</em> found that creatine supplementation improved working memory and processing speed more significantly in female participants. The brain uses 20% of the body's ATP — creatine supports this demand.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Bone Density Support</h3>
        <p>Creatine combined with resistance training may improve bone mineral density — critical for women who face 4x higher osteoporosis risk than men. A 2015 study in <em>Medicine & Science in Sports & Exercise</em> showed improved bone formation markers in postmenopausal women supplementing creatine during a resistance training program.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Mood & Mental Health</h3>
        <p>Emerging research links creatine to improved serotonin function. A 2012 study in the <em>American Journal of Psychiatry</em> found that creatine augmentation of SSRI treatment accelerated antidepressant response in women with major depressive disorder — an effect not observed in men.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="fitness" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Post-Menopause Muscle Retention</h3>
        <p>After menopause, women lose muscle mass at an accelerated rate due to declining estrogen. Creatine supplementation during resistance training helps preserve lean mass and maintain metabolic rate during this critical transition period.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Menstrual Cycle Performance</h3>
        <p>Some research suggests creatine may help counteract the performance dip during the late luteal phase (premenstrual) by supporting ATP regeneration during a period of elevated metabolic demand and increased fatigue.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="target" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Strength Without Bulk</h3>
        <p>Women have ~10% the testosterone of men, making hypertrophy (muscle growth) a much slower process. Creatine increases strength and power output without proportional muscle size increase — the result is a lean, toned, stronger physique.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- MYTH BUSTING -->
    <h2>Debunking the Myths</h2>

