    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Creatine Gummies for Women — FAQ</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is creatine safe for women?</summary><p>Yes. Over 500 studies confirm creatine's safety at 3-5g per day. The ISSN position stand explicitly states creatine is safe for both sexes. Long-term studies show no adverse effects on kidney function, liver function, or hormonal balance in women.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Will creatine make women look bulky?</summary><p>No. Women have ~10% the testosterone of men, making masculine bulk physiologically impossible from creatine. The 1-3 lbs of intracellular water weight makes muscles appear fuller and more toned, not bulky.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does creatine cause bloating in women?</summary><p>Creatine causes intracellular water retention inside muscle cells — not visible subcutaneous bloating. GI-related bloating is caused by excessive doses or empty-stomach consumption. Gummies at 3g/day avoid both issues.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How much creatine should a woman take?</summary><p>3-5 grams per day. Start at 3g and increase if tolerated. Skip the loading phase — full saturation takes 3-4 weeks at maintenance dose. No evidence suggests women need less than men.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does creatine affect the menstrual cycle?</summary><p>No. Research shows no adverse effects on menstrual regularity, reproductive hormones, or fertility. Creatine may actually help counteract the performance dip during the late luteal (premenstrual) phase.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What are women-specific creatine benefits?</summary><p>Cognitive enhancement (greater response in women), bone density support, mood/depression improvement (augments SSRI response), and post-menopausal muscle retention — on top of universal strength and power gains.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Why are creatine gummies popular with women?</summary><p>No mixing, no shaker bottles, pre-dosed servings, pleasant taste, and portable format. Create reports 68% of their gummy customers are women. Gummies remove the aesthetic and practical barriers to adoption.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can pregnant women take creatine gummies?</summary><p>Insufficient human studies exist to recommend creatine during pregnancy or breastfeeding. While creatine is naturally present in food, supplemental doses (3-5g/day) during pregnancy are unstudied. Consult your OB-GYN.</p></details>
    </section>

